f prior knowledge.</li>\n\n','','','',0,'L',0,0),(3,2,707526347757402673,707531032503741546,0,'C','Sample Report','<p><a href=\"http://www.yourgenebio.com/demo/rna-resequecing/analysis_report.htm\" target=\"_blank\">RNA Sequencing</a>。','','','',0,'L',0,0),(4,2,707526347757402673,707531032503741546,0,'T','Sequencing Strategies','','','','',0,'',0,0),(5,2,707526347757402673,707531032503741546,0,'H','','<table style=\"border: 3px solid #fa8072; width: 100%;\" border=\"3\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<div class=\"tc\">&nbsp;&nbsp;Applications</div>\n</td>\n<td>&nbsp;mRNA Sequencing&nbsp;</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<div class=\"tc\">&nbsp;Available Platforms</div>\n</td>\n<td>* Platforms：Proton/Illumina&nbsp;<br />* Read：Single-End/Paired-End&nbsp;<br />* Read length：100-300pb</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<div class=\"tc\">&nbsp;Throughput/Coverage</div>\n</td>\n<td>&nbsp;5G</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<div class=\"tc\">&nbsp;&nbsp;Limitation</div>\n</td>\n<td>&nbsp;Reference Sequence is required</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>','','','',0,'',0,0),(6,2,707526347757402673,707531032503741546,0,'T','Sample Required','','','','',0,'',0,0),(1,2,707526350014537161,707725031370314447,0,'H','','The long chain non-coding RNAs (hereinafter referred to long non-coding RNAs, lncRNAs) are RNAs of which length is greater than 200nt and not involved in protein coding. They are widely distributed in vivo. lncRNAs are involved in various biological process, including epigenetic, the transcriptional and post-transcriptional regulation. They have an important role in life activity. Because most lncRNAs do not have polyA tail structure, conventional RNA-Seq method by using Oligo dT magnetic beads for polyA enrichment cannot obtain lncRNA information comprehensively. The long chain non-coding RNA sequencing (lncRNA-Seq) is a research method which uses a specific approach such as the Ribo-ZeroTM Series Kit, to firstly reduce rRNA in the sample, then constructs the library based on the enriched RNA, finally perform the bioinformatics analysis on the high-throughput sequencing data output. Therefore lncRNA information in specific biological processes (such as development, disease, etc.) can be fully and accurately obtained.<br /><br />Through the use of high-throughput sequencing technology combined with our advanced bioinformatics analysis, almost all lncRNAs can be captured in one sequencing run. With this technology, researchers can not only quantitate the lncRNAs but also predict the novel lncRNAs in their samples. This technology provides you a brand-new tool for comprehensive, in-depth study of lncRNAs functionality.&nbsp;\n<div class=\"tc\"><img src=\"/UpFiles/2/Messagess00_Pics707526350014537161/lncRNA_regulation1_900.png\" alt=\" \" /></div>\n<div class=\"tl\">&nbsp;</div>\n<div class=\"tr\">Nature Reviews Genetics. 2009 Feb (10): 155-159</div>','','','',0,'',0,0),(5,2,707526350014537161,707725031370314447,0,'H','','<table style=\"border: 3px solid #fa8072; width: 100%;\" border=\"3\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td width=\"111\">\n<div class=\"tc\">&nbsp;Applications</div>\n</td>\n<td width=\"446\">\n<p>&nbsp;Long NonCoding RNA Sequencing</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\"111\">\n<div class=\"tc\">&nbsp;Available Platforms</div>\n</td>\n<td width=\"446\">\n<p>&nbsp;*Platform：Illumina<br />&nbsp;*Read：Paired-end<br />&nbsp;*Read length：125bp</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\"111\">\n<div class=\"tc\">Throughput/Coverage</div>\n</td>\n<td width=\"446\">\n<p>&nbsp;5G</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\"111\">\n<div class=\"tc\">&nbsp;Limitation</div>\n</td>\n<td width=\"446\">\n<p>&nbsp;Reference Sequence is required</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>','','','',0,'',0,0),(6,2,707526350014537161,707725031370314447,0,'T','Sample Required','','','','',0,'',0,0),(7,2,707526350014537161,707725031370314447,0,'H','','<img src=\"/UpFiles/2/Messagess00_Pics707526350014537161/樣品需求_mRNA_library_and_starnd_specific_RNA_library3.png\" alt=\" \" />','','','',0,'',0,0),(8,2,707526350014537161,707725031370314447,0,'T','Bioinformatics Solution','','','','',0,'',0,0),(9,2,707526350014537161,707725031370314447,0,'H','','<div class=\"viewport tc\">\n<table style=\"border: 3px solid #ffa500; width: 100%;\" border=\"3\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td width=\"89\">\n<div align=\"center\">Sample type</div>\n</td>\n<td width=\"104\">\n<div align=\"center\">Application</div>\n</td>\n<td width=\"112\">\n<div align=\"center\">Bioinformatics analysis</div>\n</td>\n<td width=\"707\">\n<div align=\"center\">Service Solution</div>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"width: 230px;\" rowspan=\"8\">\n<p align=\"center\">RNA</p>\n</td>\n<td style=\"width: 230px;\" rowspan=\"8\">\n<p align=\"center\">RNA sequencing</p>\n</td>\n<td style=\"width: 230px;\" rowspan=\"3\">\n<p align=\"center\">Basic</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\"707\">\n<p>&nbsp;● Quality trim</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\"707\">\n<p>&nbsp;●&nbsp;Mapping to reference genome</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\"707\">\n<p>&nbsp;●&nbsp;Gene expression</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td rowspan=\"5\" width=\"112\">\n<p align=\"center\">Advanced</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\"707\">\n<p>&nbsp;●&nbsp;Quality trimmed</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\"707\">\n<p>&nbsp;●&nbsp;Mapping to reference genome</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\"707\">\n<p>&nbsp;●&nbsp;Gene expression</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\"707\">\n<p>&nbsp;●&nbsp;Differential expression analysis</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\"707\">\n<p>&nbsp;●&nbsp;GO analysis for genes with significantly different expression level</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n</div>\n<div class=\"tr\">&nbsp;</div>','','','',0,'',0,0),(2,2,707526350014537161,707725031370314447,0,'C','Applications','<ul style=\"list-style-type:square;\"><li>Screening of disease-specific markers and functional genomics research are the main applications of noncoding RNA research. <li> chromatin motification<li>Transcription regulation</li>','','','',0,'L',0,0),(3,2,707526350014537161,707725031370314447,0,'C','Sample Report','<p><a href=\"http://www.yourgenebio.com/demo/lnc-rna/analysis_report.htm\" target=\"_blank\">LncRNA Sequencing</a>','','','',0,'L',0,0),(4,2,707526350014537161,707725031370314447,0,'T','Sequencing Strategies','','','','',0,'',0,0),(1,2,707526350052411125,707531032360054257,0,'C','','If the research subject is of unknown species, and the analysis is targeted at mRNA level, it needs to conduct de novo assembly, the aim of which is to assemble the possible transcriptome information for the specific species. It is also known as reference-free assembly because it doesn’t use any genome or other annotation information of the source species during the analysis process. That is also why the de novo assembly is more complicated and difficult than the analysis procedure for the known species. Also, the difference between the analysis and the actual condition might be greater. However, all these potential factors don’t affect the overwhelming advantages when analyzing the samples of unknown species. \n\nGenerally, the de novo assembly includes the following steps: Firstly, we obtain multiple sequences of short fragments after NGS, which include plenty of the transcriptional information for the sample. Before conducting analysis, we go through the quality screening to filter the sequences of poor quality to guarantee information credibility. The screened sequences will be assembled to generate many possible transcripts. Next, we compare the assembly results with the existing database and grant each transcript with possible annotation. Moreover, we further compare the sequences with the assembly results and assess the expression based on the number of sequences compared on each transcript. Finally, we can also conduct differential expression analysis (including gene ontology and pathway analysis) based on the experimental design of the customer. \n\nOn the whole, regarding the gene expression research for the unknown species, we can use the sequence obtained by NGS and take advantage of the de novo assembly method to obtain the transcriptional information of the sample and further assess the expression of various possible genes. Therefore, with the above method, we can interpret the whole transcriptome for the unknown species quickly, or compare the gene profiling between different unknown species. It shows the fitness during the analysis procedure. In addition, compared with microarray that requires probe design based on known sequence, de novo assembly can overcome this restriction to provide a more powerful method for the researches exploring the unknown species. \n','','','',0,'L',0,0),(4,2,707526350231272401,707532637766617652,0,'C','Sample Report','<a href=\"http://www.yourgenebio.com/demo/bisulfite/analysis_report.htm\" target=\"_blank\">DNA Methylation Sequencing</a>','','','',0,'L',0,0),(5,2,707526350231272401,707532637766617652,0,'T','Sequencing Strategies','','','','',0,'',0,0),(6,2,707526350231272401,707532637766617652,0,'H','','<table style=\"border: 3px solid #fa8072; width: 100%;\" border=\"3\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td width=\"111\">\n<div class=\"tc\">Applications</div>\n</td>\n<td width=\"446\">\n<p>&nbsp;DNA Methylation sequencing</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\"111\">\n<div class=\"tc\">Available Platforms</div>\n</td>\n<td width=\"446\">\n<p>&nbsp;* Platforms：Proton/Illumina<br />&nbsp;* Read：Single-End/Paired-End<br />&nbsp;* Read length：100-300pb</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\"111\">\n<div class=\"tc\">Throughput/Coverage</div>\n</td>\n<td width=\"446\">\n<p>&nbsp;30X</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\"111\">\n<div class=\"tc\">Limitation</div>\n</td>\n<td width=\"446\">\n<p>&nbsp;Reference Sequence is required</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>','','','',0,'',0,0),(2,2,707526350231272401,707532637766617652,0,'H','','<div class=\"tc\"><img src=\"/UpFiles/2/Messagess00_Pics707526350231272401/Bisulfite_C-U_en2.png\" alt=\" \" /></div>','','','',0,'',0,0),(3,2,707526350231272401,707532637766617652,0,'C','Applications','<ul style=\"list-style-type:square;\"><li>Epigenetic research<li>Tumor markers research</li>','','','',0,'L',0,0),(1,2,707526350231272401,707532637766617652,0,'H','','DNA methylation is one of the major patterns of epigenetic modification, which is widely involved in the expression and regulation of genes and genomes. DNA methylation generally existing in the bio-circle is needed by the plants and mammals for normal growth and development. For the plants, DNA methylation plays a critical role in the process of gene expression and cellular differentiation. It mainly researches the regulation of gene expression during plant development and prevention of external sequence insertion, so as to maintain the stability of the plant genome. For mammals, DNA methylation usually occurs on CpG dinucleotide. It mainly researches the gene regulation and the key biomarker for methylation that may cause diseases. <br />\n<div class=\"tc\"><img src=\"/UpFiles/2/Messagess00_Pics707526350231272401/甲基化_2.png\" alt=\" \" /></div>\n<br />A thorough understanding of DNA methylation level and position may greatly help the research on individual development and disease phenotype. <br />Take cancer as an example. CpG islands of normal cells are usually in the non &ndash;methylated state. When it turns into a cancer cell, hypermethylation will be detected in the local position of the CpG islands. It was found from research that hypermethylation of CpG islands in the promoter area will suppress the expression of the cancer suppressor gene, which further increases the probability of turning into a cancer cell. Therefore, the analysis of DNA methylation becomes a critical tool for cancer study. Besides the exploration of cancer mechanisms, it can also be used to find out proper biomarkers, providing new research directions for early-stage detection, cancer classification and grade, development of treatment drug, and prognosis assessment for cancer.&nbsp;\n<div class=\"tc\"><img src=\"/UpFiles/2/Messagess00_Pics707526350231272401/甲基化DNA1.png\" alt=\" \" /><br /><br />Nature Reviews Genetics (2005) 6:598</div>','','','',0,'',0,0),(1,2,707526350302550331,707531025372700451,0,'H','','Metagenomics proposed by Handelsman et al. (1998) refers to the entire set of genetic materials of an organism living in a specific environment. Over the past two decades, metagenomics has gradually become a special tool used in the research on microbial diversity and functionality, especially for the fungal samples from soil, marine and digestive tracts. The metagenomics mainly conducts researches on microbes. Since more than 99% of microbes can&rsquo;t be cultivated manually, the most effective way to describe the metabolic profiling in an actual environment is directly extracting the genetic material in the environment (including DNA and RNA) for analysis. Such genome information can help to get an overall understanding of the metabolic pathway in the environment. Due to the complicated species in the environment, it will take a lot of time and funds if interpreting the genetic message with traditional sequencing method. On the contrary, NGS can generate a large amount of sequencing data, which is an efficient analysis tool for the genome in a highly complicated environment. Our body and food are full of pathogens, allergens and beneficial microbes. The genome application on organisms living in such environment shall not be limited to humans.&nbsp;<br /><img src=\"/UpFiles/2/Messagess00_Pics707526350302550331/metagenomics1.png\" alt=\" \" /><br />\n<div class=\"tc\"><img src=\"/UpFiles/2/Messagess00_Pics707526350302550331/metagenomics_shotgun_900.png\" alt=\" \" /></div>\n<br /><br /><br />','','','',0,'',0,0),(2,2,707526350302550331,707531025372700451,0,'C','Applications','<ul style=\"list-style-type:square;\"><li>Research on metabolic characteristics and types of microbes in the environment.</li>','','','',0,'L',0,0),(3,2,707526350302550331,707531025372700451,0,'C','Sample Report','<a href=\"http://www.yourgenebio.com/demo/meta-genomic/analysis_report.htm\" target=\"_blank\">Metagenomic Shotgun sequencing</a>。','','','',0,'L',0,0),(4,2,707526350302550331,707531025372700451,0,'T','Sequencing Strategies','','','','',0,'',0,0),(5,2,707526350302550331,707531025372700451,0,'H','','<table style=\"border: 3px solid #fa8072; width: 100%;\" border=\"3\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td width=\"111\">\n<div class=\"tc\">Applications</div>\n</td>\n<td width=\"446\">\n<p>&nbsp;Metagenomic&nbsp;&nbsp;(whole genome shotgun)</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\"111\">\n<div class=\"tc\">Available Platforms</div>\n</td>\n<td width=\"446\">\n<p>&nbsp;* Platforms：Illumina&nbsp;<br />&nbsp;* Read：Paired-End&nbsp;<br />&nbsp;* Read length：250-300pb</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\"111\">\n<div class=\"tc\">Throughput/Coverage</div>\n</td>\n<td width=\"446\">\n<p>&nbsp;5G</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\"111\">\n<div class=\"tc\">Limitation</div>\n</td>\n<td width=\"446\">\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>','','','',0,'',0,0),(1,1,655406000205656404,655407624040323510,0,'Y','','https://youtu.be/AHHZUbataKc','<h5>衛福部公布101年新罹癌人數及排名，發現每5分鐘26秒，就有一個人罹癌。比前101年快了十四秒，平均每233名國人就有1人罹癌。</h5>','','',0,'',1300,250),(8,2,707526350310726363,707532647572537741,0,'T','Bioinformatics Solution','','','','',0,'',0,0),(9,2,707526350310726363,707532647572537741,0,'H','','<table style=\"border: 3px solid #ffa500; width: 100%;\" border=\"3\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\"><colgroup><col width=\"89\" /><col width=\"119\" /><col width=\"171\" /><col width=\"104\" /><col width=\"484\" /></colgroup>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td class=\"oa1\" width=\"89\" height=\"38\">\n<div class=\"tc\">Sample type</div>\n</td>\n<td class=\"oa1\" colspan=\"2\" width=\"290\">\n<div class=\"tc\">Application</div>\n</td>\n<td class=\"oa1\" width=\"104\">\n<div class=\"tc\">Bioinformatics analysis</div>\n</td>\n<td class=\"oa1\" width=\"484\">\n<div class=\"tc\">Service Solution</div>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td class=\"oa3\" style=\"width: 230px; height: 239px;\" rowspan=\"12\">\n<div class=\"tc\">DNA</div>\n</td>\n<td class=\"oa3\" style=\"width: 230px;\" rowspan=\"12\">\n<div class=\"tc\">Metagenomics</div>\n</td>\n<td class=\"oa3\" style=\"width: 230px;\" rowspan=\"5\">\n<div class=\"tc\">Shotgun sequencing</div>\n</td>\n<td class=\"oa3\" style=\"width: 230px;\" rowspan=\"5\">\n<div class=\"tc\">Advanced</div>\n</td>\n<td class=\"oa4\" width=\"484\">\n<p>&nbsp;● Quality trimmed</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td class=\"oa5\" width=\"484\" height=\"16\">\n<p>&nbsp;●&nbsp;De novo assembly</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td class=\"oa5\" width=\"484\" height=\"17\">\n<p>&nbsp;●&nbsp;Taxonomy&nbsp;analysis</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td class=\"oa5\" width=\"484\" height=\"16\">\n<p>&nbsp;●&nbsp;ORF prediction</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td class=\"oa6\" width=\"484\" height=\"29\">\n<p>&nbsp;●&nbsp;Gene annotation (BLAST to NR database)</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td class=\"oa3\" rowspan=\"7\" width=\"171\" height=\"145\">\n<div class=\"tc\">16S rRNA /target&nbsp;<br />sequencing</div>\n</td>\n<td class=\"oa3\" rowspan=\"7\" width=\"104\">\n<div class=\"tc\">Advanced</div>\n</td>\n<td class=\"oa4\" width=\"484\">\n<p>&nbsp;●&nbsp;Demultiplex by specific barcode</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td class=\"oa5\" width=\"484\" height=\"29\">\n<p>&nbsp;●&nbsp;Reads processing&nbsp;<br />(reads trimming &amp; merging overlapped read pairs)</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td class=\"oa5\" width=\"484\" height=\"19\">\n<p>&nbsp;●&nbsp;OTU clustering</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td class=\"oa5\" width=\"484\" height=\"17\">\n<p>&nbsp;●&nbsp;Remove chimeric OTUs</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td class=\"oa5\" width=\"484\" height=\"16\">\n<p>&nbsp;●&nbsp;Assign taxonomy to OTUs</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td class=\"oa5\" width=\"484\" height=\"29\">\n<p>&nbsp;●&nbsp;Community analysis (Taxonomy analysis)</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td class=\"oa6\" width=\"484\" height=\"17\">\n<p>&nbsp;●&nbsp;Rarefraction analysis</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>','','','',0,'',0,0),(1,2,707526350310726363,707532647572537741,0,'H','','<div class=\"tc\"><img src=\"/UpFiles/2/Messagess00_Pics707526350310726363/16s_rRNA.png\" alt=\" \" /></div>\n<div class=\"tc\"><img src=\"/UpFiles/2/Messagess00_Pics707526350310726363/Metagenomics_16S.png\" alt=\" \" /></div>','','','',0,'',0,0),(2,2,707526350310726363,707532647572537741,0,'C','Applications','<ul style=\"list-style-type:square;\"><li> Understanding distribution and diversity of species.</il>','','','',0,'L',0,0),(1,2,707526350320106753,707532647712763717,0,'T','A Powerful Platform for Automated, Whole Genome Mapping','','','','',0,'',0,0),(2,2,707526350320106753,707532647712763717,0,'H','','<div class=\"tc\"><img style=\"text-align: center;\" src=\"/UpFiles/1/Messagess00_Pics655643254646267540/banner-opgen.png\" alt=\" \" /></div>\n<p>Optical Mapping is a powerful technology for whole genome mapping that rapidly generates high-resolution, ordered, whole genome restriction maps without reference sequence from single DNA molecules. Optical Mapping can be performed on bacteria, yeast or fungi, and can find the unexpected information, such as genomic rearrangements and modifications to genomic architecture and novel discovery, independent of prior sequence information.</p>','','','',0,'',0,0),(3,2,707526350320106753,707532647712763717,0,'T','Applications of Optical Mapping','','','','',0,'',0,0),(4,2,707526350320106753,707532647712763717,0,'H','','<table style=\"width: 100%;\" cellspacing=\"15\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>1. Strain Typing<br /><br /></strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<div class=\"tc\"><img src=\"/UpFiles/2/Messagess00_Pics707526350320106753/OM21.png\" alt=\" \" /><img src=\"/UpFiles/2/Messagess00_Pics707526350320106753/OM31.png\" alt=\" \" /></div>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>For strain characterizing and monitoring strain stability, determining genetic relatedness between multiple microbial isolates, and differentiating and visualizing genomic differences between the strains. Optical mapping tracks and links outbreak or potential contamination strains to the responsible source</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>','','','',0,'',0,0),(5,2,707526350320106753,707532647712763717,0,'H','','<span class=\"font_bold\">2. Comparative Genomics</span><br />\n<table style=\"width: 100%;\" border=\"0\" cellspacing=\"25\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"width: 500px;\"><img src=\"/UpFiles/2/Messagess00_Pics707526350320106753/OM4.png\" alt=\" \" /></td>\n<td>For analyzing and comparing genomes from different strains to better understand gene function and relatedness. Find insertions, deletions, and intragenomic reshuffling of segments of genomic sequences such as inversions, transpositions, duplications and rearrangements. Identify and track mobile genetic elements like phage and transposons.</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<br /><strong>3.Whole Genome Sequence Assembly</strong><br />\n<table style=\"width: 100%;\" border=\"0\" cellspacing=\"15\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"width: 500px;\"><img src=\"/UpFiles/2/Messagess00_Pics707526350320106753/OM5.png\" alt=\" \" /></td>\n<td>For accelerating sequence assembly by aligning sequence contigs to an Optical Map scaffold to rapidly order and orientate sequences. Misassemblies can be identified, corrected and orientated properly to rapidly locate and close gaps. Complementary to sequencing technologies, Optical Mapping is used to survey genomic architecture prior to sequencing, thereby reducing the number sequence runs required for whole genome analysis. Additionally, Optical Mapping is an independent validation method for sequencing projects.</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>','','','',0,'',0,0),(1,2,70752634102164366